<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-694-497 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 694 497</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  April 15 1991 v220 n15 pS7(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PBX Plus Services: a new way to get Centrex in the door. (Buildingon a Solid Foundation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local exchange carriers (LEC) can obtain business from PBX usersand increase Centrex access lines by targeting the $4.4-billionPBX aftermarket.andP;  LECs must overcome several obstacles whenattempting to obtain the business of PBX users, includingcustomers' reluctance to implement a new system, customers'unfamiliarity with LECs' services, and LEC account executives'inability to gain access to PBX users.andP;  LECs can solve PBX users'business problems by using a PBX Plus Services marketing program,which allows Centrex to offer benefits to PBX users by providingthem with add-on voice lines, automatic call distribution, voicemessaging, or data communications services.andP;  This strategy worksbecause PBX customers gain additional capacity without having toreplace their PBX systems.andP;  LECs that have adopted the PBX PlusServices concept include Southern Bell and Ameritech Services.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Southern Bell Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Marketing)Ameritech Services Inc. (Marketing).andO;Topic:     Local CommunicationTelecommunications ServicesMarketing StrategyPBXEnhancementsCommon CarriersTelephone companiesCentrex telephone service.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>